ymr wm_q_v &lt;- poly2nb(v_data,                  queen=TRUE) summary(wm_q_v)}
It shows that there are 258 villages in the selected Tainan Area. The most connected area has 14 links. All of the villages at least has 2 neighbors.



ymr rswm_q_v &lt;- nb2listw(wm_q_v,                     style="W",                     zero.policy = TRUE) rswm_q_v}






ymr moran.test(v_data$total_cases,             listw=rswm_q_v,             zero.policy = TRUE,             na.action=na.omit)}
As the p-value is very low, which is statistically significant. We can reject the null hypothesis that there is significant spatial autocorrelation in the data.



ymr set.seed(1234) bperm_v = moran.mc(v_data$total_cases,                  listw=rswm_q_v,                  nsim=999,                  zero.policy = TRUE,                  na.action=na.omit) bperm_v}
As the p-value is very low, which is statistically significant. We can reject the null hypothesis that there is significant spatial autocorrelation in the data.






ymr hist(bperm_v$res,       freq=TRUE,       breaks=20,       xlab="Simulated Moran's I") abline(v=0,         col="red")}






ymr geary.test(v_data$total_cases, listw=rswm_q_v)}



ymr set.seed(1234) bperm_v_geary =geary.mc(v_data$total_cases,                 listw=rswm_q_v,                 nsim=999) bperm_v_geary}
As the p-value is very low, which is statistically significant. We can reject the null hypothesis that there is significant spatial autocorrelation in the data.






ymr hist(bperm_v_geary$res, freq=TRUE, breaks=20, xlab="Simulated Geary c") abline(v=1, col="red")}

